@jennie
In the UK at least, the chemical changes in cooking are covered - eg protein denatures if it is overcooked - knowing the science gives insight into how we cook. Also, how various ingredients interact and why. There's also nutrition, digestion and food safety. This last covers why food spoils - microorganisms like bacteria, spores, moulds; enzyme reactions, oxidation, optimum temperatures for storage.

And there's not a lot of actual sewing - it's about the textiles, their composition and their properties, how they combine for different uses, how they are manufactured - setting up a loom requires programing skills.

@jennie

They do more hard science than you’d think, at least here in the UK. Enough for my son (13) to laugh at my lame cooking/chemistry joke when he burned some cookies… the Maillard reaction has gone to completion! 

There’s also a lot on safe cooking temperatures, including bacteria destruction rates at various heat levels and durations.

